  <title>toponymic name-descriptions</title>
  <p>Toponymic name-descriptions are <a href="?xx=nouns/name_descriptions">name-descriptions</a> which are also <a href="?xx=nouns/toponyms">toponyms</a>, 
    i.e. they are definite common noun phrases used to name places and other geographical entities.</p>
  <p>Like other name-descriptions, toponymic name-descriptions can be classified into two <u>grammatical</u> types –</p>
  <ul>
    <li><u>pre-specified</u> toponymic name-descriptions 
      eg. <m>An t-Àth Leathann</m> <en>Broadford</en>, <m>A’ Chomraich</m> <en>Applecross</en>, <m>An Agaidh Mhòr</m> <en>Aviemore</en></li>
    <li><u>post-specified</u> toponymic name-descriptions 
      eg. <m>Baile Bhòid</m> <en>Rothesay</en>, <m>Baile nan Granndach</m> <en>Grantown-on-Spey</en>, <m>Baile Ailein</m> <en>Balallan</en>,
      <m>Baile an t-Sealgair</m> <en>Hunterston</en>, <m>Baile Ùr an t-Slèibhe</m> <en>Newtonmore</en>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>Like other toponyms, toponymic name-descriptions can be classified <u>semantically</u> according to the kind of geographical entity they refer to –</p>
  <ul>
    <li>islands and districts eg. </li>
    <li>towns and settlements eg. </li>
    <li>countries and continents eg. </li>
  </ul>
  
  
